\f0\b\fs26 \cf2 Introduction
\f1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\ri720\partightenfactor0

\b0\fs12 \cf0 \
\pard\pardeftab720\ri720\partightenfactor0

\fs20 \cf0 EVOLVE is a computer program that allows you to experiment with evolution and to get quick results in a fashion that is impossible to do in any other way.  You may control the starting population, overall population size, natural selection, pattern of inheritance and migration in a hypothetical population. By experimenting with EVOLVE you will develop:\
\pard\pardeftab720\ri720\partightenfactor0

\fs6 \cf0 \
\pard\pardeftab720\li216\fi-216\ri720\partightenfactor0
\ls1\ilvl0
\fs20 \cf0 a better understanding of evolutionary processes and their interactions, \
a firmer grasp of some important concepts of Mendelian genetics,\
some understanding of experimental design, and \
of the use of models, plus\
an appreciation for one of the many uses of computers in biology.\
\pard\pardeftab720\ri720\partightenfactor0
\cf0 \
\pard\pardeftab720\ri720\partightenfactor0

\f0\b \cf2 BASIC EVOLUTIONARY CONCEPTS as Used in EVOLVE\
\pard\pardeftab720\ri720\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0\fs6 \cf0 \
\pard\pardeftab720\li216\fi-216\ri720\partightenfactor0
\ls2\ilvl0
\fs20 \cf0 A 
\i\b Species
\i0\b0  can be conceived of as a metapopulation, a set of more\'96or\'96less isolated subpopulations that are capable of reproducing within & amongst themselves and which cannot reproduce with other species. EVOLVE simulates a metapopulation with one or more subpopulations.\
\pard\pardeftab720\li432\fi-216\ri720\partightenfactor0
\ls3\ilvl0\cf0 Each population in a metapopulation has 1 
\i\b Gene
\i0\b0  that affects 1 or more traits (e.g., pigments, proteins, etc.)\
\pard\pardeftab720\li648\fi-216\ri720\partightenfactor0
\ls4\ilvl0\cf0 Genes may have 2 or 3 
\i\b Alleles
\i0\b0   (usu. more in nature) symbolized by A, B, C. Alleles have \
\pard\pardeftab720\li936\fi-288\ri720\partightenfactor0
\ls5\ilvl0
\i\b \cf0 Mutation Rates
\i0\b0  (A\'96>B, B\'96>A, A\'96>C, C\'96>A, B\'96>C, C\'96>B)\
\ls5\ilvl0
\i\b Patterns of inheritance
\i0\b0 , determined by interactions between alleles and include\
\pard\pardeftab720\li1080\fi-216\ri720\partightenfactor0
\ls6\ilvl0
\i\b \cf0 Dominant\'96Recessive
\i0\b0 : heterozygote has same phenotype as dominant homozygote, recessive phenotype is homozygous recessive. E.g., if AA = 5, AB = 5, BB = 10, A is dominant, B is recessive\
\ls6\ilvl0
\i\b Incomplete Dominance
\i0\b0 : heterozygote is in between phenotypes of homozygotes. E.g., If AA = 5, AB = 8, BB = 10, alleles are incompletely dominant.\
\ls6\ilvl0
\i\b Codominance
\i0\b0 : heterozygote displays phenotypes of both homozygotes. E.g., AA = Protein1, BB 
\i\b =
\i0\b0  Protein 2, AB = Proteins 1 & 2.\
\ls6\ilvl0
\i\b Overdominance / Heterosis
\i0\b0  / 
\i\b Heterozygote superiority
\i0\b0 : heterozygote phenotype is more extreme than either homozygote. E.g., AA = 5, AB = 13, BB =8\
\ls6\ilvl0
\i\b Underdominance
\i0\b0  / 
\i\b Heterozygote inferiority:
\i0\b0  heterozygote phenotype is less extreme than either homozygote. E.g., AA = 5, AB = 3, BB = 10\
\pard\pardeftab720\ri720\partightenfactor0

\fs6 \cf0 \
\pard\pardeftab720\li432\fi-216\ri720\partightenfactor0
\ls7\ilvl0
\fs20 \cf0 A Population consists of 
\i\b Organisms. 
\i0\b0 \
\pard\pardeftab720\li648\fi-216\ri720\partightenfactor0
\ls8\ilvl0\cf0 Ea. Organism has 2 copies of each gene\
\pard\pardeftab720\li936\fi-288\ri720\partightenfactor0
\ls9\ilvl0\cf0 Thus, organisms may have one of 3 (or 6) 
\i\b Genotypes
\i0\b0  symbolized AA, AB & BB if there are 2 alleles; if there are 3 alleles, add AC, BC & CC.\
Genotypes may be 
\i\b Homozygous 
\i0\b0 (2 copies of same allele, i.e., AA, BB, CC) or  
\i\b heterozygous
\i0\b0  (2 different alleles, i.e., AB, AC, BC)\
\pard\pardeftab720\li648\fi-216\ri720\partightenfactor0
\ls10\ilvl0\cf0 Organisms have 
\i\b Phenotypes
\i0\b0 : observable traits (e.g., pigments, proteins, structures, behaviors, etc.) produced by their genotype. Phenotypes of interest in EVOLVE include:\
\pard\pardeftab720\li936\fi-288\ri720\partightenfactor0
\ls11\ilvl0
\i\b \cf0 Survival rate
\i0\b0  (genotype\'92s avg. proportion of young surviving to adulthood)\
\ls11\ilvl0
\i\b Reproductive rate
\i0\b0  (genotype\'92s avg. number of young / adult)\
\ls11\ilvl0
\i\b Absolute Fitness 
\i0\b0 (genotype\'92s Survival Rate * its Reproductive rate) Values > 1 result in increasing population size, values < 1 result in population decline; they may go to extinction.\
\ls11\ilvl0
\i\b Relative Fitness 
\i0\b0 (genotype\'92s Absolute Fitness / the maximum absolute fitness) Values 0\'961\
\ls11\ilvl0
\i\b Migration rates 
\i0\b0 (proportion of individuals with the genotype moving to another population)\
\ls11\ilvl0
\i\b Mating preferences
\i0\b0  (non\'96randomness, preference or bias in mating of one genotype with another) Values 0\'961. E.g., with 
\i outcrossing
\i0 , individuals of a genotype prefer to mate with individuals unlike themselves. In a 2\'96allele population, AA individuals might proportionally mate 50% with BB, 40% with AB and 10% with AA.
\i\b \
\pard\pardeftab720\li216\fi-216\ri720\partightenfactor0
\ls12\ilvl0\cf0 Evolution 
\i0\b0 is defined as a change in the genetic makeup of a population, i.e., a change in allele or genotype frequencies.\
\pard\pardeftab720\ri720\partightenfactor0
\cf0 \
\pard\pardeftab720\ri720\partightenfactor0

\f0\b \cf2 Hardy\'96Weinberg Equilibrium Concept
\f1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\ri720\partightenfactor0

\b0\fs12 \cf0 \
\pard\pardeftab720\li216\fi-216\ri720\partightenfactor0
\ls13\ilvl0
\fs20 \cf0 A population can be modeled as a 
\i\b Gene Pool
\i0\b0  made up of all of the alleles in a population. Gene Pools have\
\pard\pardeftab720\li432\fi-216\ri720\partightenfactor0
\ls14\ilvl0
\i\b \cf0 Allele Frequencies
\i0\b0 , the proportion of all alleles in a population  that are a specific allele; e.g., the frequency of A = the number of A alleles / the total number of alleles.Traditionally, p = freq. A, q = freq. B, r = freq. C), by definition, p + q = 1 in a 2\'96allele population or p + q + r = 1 in a 3\'96allele population.\
\ls14\ilvl0
\i\b Genotype frequencies, 
\i0\b0 the proportion of all genotypes that are a specific genotype; e.g., freq. of AA = number of AA / Total population size.
\i\b \
Mating
\i0\b0  consists of randomly sampling pairs of alleles without replacement from the gene pool to produce the young of the next generation.\
\pard\pardeftab720\li216\fi-216\ri720\partightenfactor0
\ls15\ilvl0\cf0 All things being equal, allele frequencies will not change and what is sometimes called the 
\i Hardy\'96Weinberg Law
\i0  states that genotype frequencies will be\uc0\u8232 p\super 2\nosupersub  + 2pq + q\super 2 \nosupersub in a 2\'96allele population or \uc0\u8232 p\super 2\nosupersub  + 2pq + 2pr + 2qr + q\super 2\nosupersub  + r\super 2\nosupersub  in a 3\'96allele population \uc0\u8232 This is the null case of no evolution; allele and genotype frequencies won\'92t change and the population is  in 
\i Hardy\'96Weinberg equilibrium
\i0  (HW). \
However, in the real world all things are not equal. HW makes 7 assumptions: \uc0\u8232 1. initial genotype frequencies in the two sexes are equal\u8232 2. generations are discrete, i.e., do not overlap\u8232 3. population  size is infinitely large\u8232 4. mating is random\u8232 5. no differences in survival and/or reproduction, i.e., no natural selection\u8232 6. population is closed, i.e., no migration in or out of population\u8232 7. alleles do not change, i.e., no mutation\
All of these assumptions are violated in real\'96word populations. EVOLVE avoids the first two by modeling organisms that are hermaphroditic and die after reproducing;  you can experiment with the other 5 evolutionary forces:\
\pard\pardeftab720\li432\fi-216\ri720\partightenfactor0
\ls16\ilvl0
\i\b \cf0 Mutation
\i0\b0 : H\'96W assumes alleles don\'92t change, or that mutation rates from one allele to another are equal. Mutations do occur in the real world and generate the genetic variation essential for evolution to occur.\
\ls16\ilvl0
\i\b Natural selection:
\i0\b0  H\'96W assumes there are no differences in allele/genotype survival or reproduction. This of course is often violated and allows populations to adapt to their environments.\
\ls16\ilvl0
\i\b Gene Flow:
\i0\b0  H\'96W assumes the population is closed, i.e., there is no differential emigration/immigration of alleles/genotypes between populations.\
\ls16\ilvl0
\i\b Genetic Drift:
\i0\b0  H\'96W assumes the population is infinitely large. Any real population is finite and subsequent generations are a more\'96or\'96less accurate samples of the alleles present in the previous generation\'92s gene pool.\
\ls16\ilvl0
\i\b Sexual Selection / Non\'96Random mating: 
\i0\b0 H\'96W assumes there are no differences in probability of genotypes mating w/ ea. other.\
\pard\pardeftab720\ri720\partightenfactor0
\cf0 \
\pard\pardeftab720\ri720\partightenfactor0

\f0\b \cf2 Modeled Organisms
\f1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\ri720\partightenfactor0

\b0\fs12 \cf0 \
\pard\pardeftab720\ri720\partightenfactor0

\fs20 \cf0 The organisms modeled by EVOLVE are assumed to\
\pard\pardeftab720\li216\fi-216\ri720\partightenfactor0
\ls17\ilvl0\cf0 Be 
\i\b Diploid
\i0\b0 : have 2 copies of a gene that has two or three alleles.\
Have 
\i\b non\'96overlapping generations
\i0\b0 : e.g., animals where adults mate, lay eggs or give birth and die before the young become adults, or annual plants that cross\'96pollinate, set seeds and die before the seeds germinate.\
\pard\pardeftab720\li216\fi-216\ri720\partightenfactor0
\ls17\ilvl0
\b \cf0 Hermaphroditic
\b0 : having male and female organs that normally mate/pollinate with another individual, but are capable of self\'96fertilizing if they cannot find a mate or are not pollinated.\
\pard\pardeftab720\li216\fi-216\ri720\partightenfactor0
\ls17\ilvl0
\i\b \cf0 Life cycle:
\i0\b0  adults mate, produce zygotes (eggs/seed/young), die. A % of young may emigrate; migration is random between populations. Immigrants are added to resident young. Young undergo selection, those that survive are adults of next generation.\
\pard\pardeftab720\li216\fi-216\ri720\partightenfactor0
\cf0 \
\pard\pardeftab720\ri720\partightenfactor0

\f0\b \cf2 EVOLVE as an Evolutionary Laboratory\
\pard\pardeftab720\ri720\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0\fs12 \cf0 \
\pard\pardeftab720\ri720\partightenfactor0

\fs20 \cf0 Perhaps it is belaboring the obvious to say that experiments in evolutionary biology are difficult -- you can\'92t evolve something in a semester!  Nevertheless, this is an important point because it has made the approach of evolutionary biologists somewhat different from that of many other biologists. And learning about evolution is difficult because students can\'92t "get their hands dirty" by doing experiments like those in, for example, physiology or biochemistry.\
\pard\pardeftab720\ri720\partightenfactor0

\fs6 \cf0 \
\pard\pardeftab720\ri720\partightenfactor0

\fs20 \cf0 A common, naive view of science is that experiments are required to test hypotheses. In most scientific disciplines we note some aspect of the "real world," formulate hypotheses about major factors involved in that phenomenon and test those hypotheses with experiments. Experiments essentially are simple models of the real world that hold most factors constant, vary one or a few factors, and observe the results.  In many areas of biology, experimental design has become a sophisticated and elaborate affair of choosing organisms, equipment, statistical methods, etc.\
\pard\pardeftab720\ri720\partightenfactor0

\fs6 \cf0 \
\pard\pardeftab720\ri720\partightenfactor0

\fs20 \cf0 Evolutionary biologists can apply that approach only with difficulty.  We can do classical types of experiments using small organisms with short life cycles. Occasionally we can find a situation in nature that approaches a true experiment, but it is hard to coax Ma Nature into providing us with good experimental models. However, observational tests of hypotheses are quite common in evolutionary biology, as in other historical sciences like geology and astronomy.\
\pard\pardeftab720\ri720\partightenfactor0

\fs6 \cf0 \
\pard\pardeftab720\ri720\partightenfactor0

\fs20 \cf0 Despite (or perhaps because of) difficulties with experimentation, biologists continue to develop models of evolutionary processes, many mathematical rather than experimental or observational. In essence, we simulate some aspect of the real world in mathematical, abstract form, and then manipulate the simulation to investigate its consequences. If the model is a good one, the consequences will clarify the real world. The Hardy-Weinberg formula and the mathematical population genetics that evolved from it are excellent examples of such models.  Many of these models can be programmed into computers, which brings us to EVOLVE.\
\pard\pardeftab720\ri720\partightenfactor0

\fs6 \cf0 \
\pard\pardeftab720\ri720\partightenfactor0

\fs20 \cf0 EVOLVE allows you to setup experiments that can illustrate the effects of all of the evolutionary forces on allele and genotype frequencies \'97 Genetic Drift (population size), Natural Selection (differences in reproductive success), Mutation (change of alleles), Migration (migration of alleles between subpopulations), and Sexual Selection (non\'96random or preferential mating). These may be studied individually or in combination. In addition, you may allow the population size to vary within specific ranges, which allows you to see how evolution affects a key ecological variable, the intrinsic rate of population increase.\
\pard\pardeftab720\ri720\partightenfactor0

